  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Prioritizing the Chatbot**\n\nI\'m focusing intently on the user feedback. The core need is clear: the AI assistant (chatbot) must be the central feature, not just a side element. My goal now is to shift the user experience to reflect this critical priority.\n\n\n**Re-imagining the Interface**\n\nI\'m now fully committed to a chat-first paradigm. Thinking through the user interface, it\'s clear the app needs a drastic shift. My focus is on making the AI Assistant the primary, pervasive element, drawing inspiration from platforms like ChatGPT, Claude, and Linear. The default authenticated view must be the chat interface. I need to modify `App.tsx` and routing to make the Assistant the root route, and update the layout to reflect a chat-centric view.\n\n\n**Refining the Layout**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on UI details. The `Assistant.tsx` component is the key. When it\'s empty, a prominent input prompt should be central. During conversations, the input should move to the bottom. I\'m considering integrating `Alumni` and `Insights` into this, perhaps via cards, but I\'m prioritizing a clean layout initially. Routes are being simplified; the default after login will be `/chat`. The Dashboard may be removed, or relegated to a secondary analytics view.\n\n\n**Implementing the Chat**\n\nI\'m now deep in implementation. The plan is in motion: I\'m focusing on the `store/chatStore.ts` creation to manage chat history and making it match the Claude-like sidebar. `Layout.tsx` is under redesign, focusing on a ChatGPT/Claude-inspired sidebar structure. Then `Assistant.tsx` is being refactored, focusing on centering the UI and styling the input box. Login and registration are both redirected to the `/chat` route.\n\n\n**Enhancing the Assistant**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in the Assistant\'s UI, drawing inspiration from user preferences like Apple, Linear, and Claude. When there are no messages, the Assistant must prominently display a greeting and a centered prompt, encouraging users to \"Ask AlumniIQ\". When messages exist, a standard chat interface will appear. I\'m focusing on significant enhancements to the `Assistant.tsx` component.\n\n\n\n**Designing the Sidebar**\n\nI\'m now fully focused on the sidebar design, drawing inspiration from platforms such as Claude and ChatGPT. I\'m aiming for a 260px width, a top logo, a prominent \"New Chat\" button with a glass effect, and a subsequent \"Directory\" section. I\'m focusing on the `Layout.tsx` and the `Assistant.tsx` components to integrate a sidebar to house the recent chats and provide a clear navigation structure, and to implement the \"New Chat\" button. I\'m planning out the file modifications needed to be executed.\n\n\n**Implementing the Sidebar**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the finer points of the sidebar. I\'m imagining incorporating \"Recent Threads\" (initially mocked), a user profile at the bottom, and subtle links to \"Insights.\" The goal is a sleek, intuitive design.\n\nI\'m now deep in the implementation of the `Assistant.tsx` component. When there are no messages, I intend to center \"Alumni Intelligence\" with a textarea, styled as a real prompt box, and suggestions formatted like Perplexity pills. With messages, I\'ll display them on the left, distinguishing user input from assistant responses, likely through avatars labeled \"You\" and \"AlumniIQ\", maintaining consistent left alignment. Markdown rendering is also top priority.\n\nI\'ve decided to execute on the change of the default route. `Dashboard` is gone. The default authenticated route will be `/chat`. I need to edit `Login.tsx` and `Register.tsx` to redirect there.\n\n\n**Refactoring the Routing**\n\nI\'m now changing up the application routes. I plan to remove the Dashboard and route all logged-in users directly to `/chat`, the Assistant. I\'ll need to edit `App.tsx` to handle this change, removing the now-unnecessary `Dashboard` and re-routing from there, and redirect the login/registration pages accordingly. I\'ll also modify `Layout.tsx` and `Assistant.tsx` accordingly to get all the elements in order. I\'m focusing on a chat-centric workflow. Then I am looking at reviewing the Assistant.tsx streaming implementation.\n\n\n\n**Updating the Assistant**\n\nI\'m now implementing the UI changes based on my earlier notes. The plan is in motion: The `App.tsx` file now directly routes authenticated users to `/chat`. The `Layout` component is being reconfigured, with \"New Thread\" as the top action, followed by \"Tools\" (Explorer and Insights), as in my designs. The `Assistant.tsx` is being refined to provide a centered Hero view when there are no messages, transitioning to a chat stream with messages. I also need to verify that the backend `server.ts` is sending the correct streaming format. The format is a JSON with a key `text` and the chunk of text as the value, and the parsing to handle that format. I\'m applying these changes now using my tools.\n\n\n"
